\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= 2(a - x) \cdot \frac{1}{2}(x^2 + b^2)^{-1/2} \cdot 2x \\
&\quad + 2(a - x) + 2b^2 \cdot \frac{1}{2}(x^2 + b^2)^{-1/2} \\
&= \frac{2x(a - x)}{\sqrt{x^2 + b^2}} + 2(a - x) + \frac{2b^2}{\sqrt{x^2 + b^2}} \\
&= \frac{2(a - x)(x + b^2 + \sqrt{x^2 + b^2})}{\sqrt{x^2 + b^2}} \\
\end{align*}
Setting $f'(x) = 0,$ we have:
\begin{align*}
\frac{2(a - x)(x + b^2 + \sqrt{x^2 + b^2})}{\sqrt{x^2 + b^2}} &= 0 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad (a - x)(x + b^2 + \sqrt{x^2 + b^2}) &= 0 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad x &= a
\end{align*}
Thus, $x = a$ is a critical point of $f(x).$  We now evaluate $f(x)$ at the critical point and the endpoints of the interval $[0, a].$  We have:
\begin{align*}
f(0) &= 2(a - 0)(0 + \sqrt{0^2 + b^2}) = 2ab \\
f(a) &= 2(a - a)(a + \sqrt{a^2 + b^2}) = 0 \\
\end{align*}
Thus, the absolute maximum value of $f(x)$ is $\boxed{2ab},$ which occurs at $x = a.$</think>
